00:05:20.100 --> 00:05:26.490
And that is really understanding users, building
magical experiences -- which in this case

00:05:26.490 --> 00:05:31.840
is you guys building magical applications
-- and then really connecting the two.

00:05:31.840 --> 00:05:35.620
So let's take a really kind of bizarre but
fun and specific example of how that works

00:05:35.620 --> 00:05:38.650
in reality when we talk about apps.

00:05:38.650 --> 00:05:41.210
Let's say that you're a carpenter.

00:05:41.210 --> 00:05:43.880
Or you're doing DIY in your house.

00:05:43.880 --> 00:05:48.180
And you're fixing chairs and you're hanging
frames up on your wall and you're maybe adjusting

00:05:48.180 --> 00:05:51.310
beams, you know, in your house and you're
doing all sorts of work in your house.

00:05:51.310 --> 00:05:55.380
Well, how cool would it be if when you're
putting that frame up on the wall, the one

00:05:55.380 --> 00:05:59.100
that you kind of like have to ask your wife
to sit 50 meters behind you to tell if you

00:05:59.100 --> 00:06:03.060
it's crooked or straight, how cool would it
be if you had a little application that could

00:06:03.060 --> 00:06:05.050
do that for you?

00:06:05.050 --> 00:06:07.350
Like Ben Zibble's bubble app.

00:06:07.350 --> 00:06:11.850
I could fire up my bubble app and place my
phone on top of that frame and see if the

00:06:11.850 --> 00:06:14.270
frame is perfectly aligned or not.

00:06:14.270 --> 00:06:16.130
Saves me a lot of time.

00:06:16.130 --> 00:06:21.230
Makes my life easier, and to some extent as
well, it's kind of a magical experience.

00:06:21.230 --> 00:06:26.550
The point is that applications are either
enhancing our lives or making our lives more

00:06:26.550 --> 00:06:29.430
productive, or they're entertaining us.

00:06:29.430 --> 00:06:34.000
And they do it in such a way that really has
a magical quality and component to it.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:38.490
And our role as marketers and your role as
marketers is, how do we connect those two.

00:06:38.490 --> 00:06:43.000
How do we connect the magic of the apps that
we build with, essentially, an entertaining

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:47.160
experience for a consumer or a productive
experience for consumers?

00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:52.630
But, really, before we actually get into the
nuts and bolts of the four Ps themselves,

00:06:52.630 --> 00:06:54.440
let's talk about research for a minute.

00:06:54.440 --> 00:06:59.250
Because when you talk about users, it really
starts with research.

00:06:59.250 --> 00:07:03.280
Before you even write that first line of code,
you really have to understand who your consumers

00:07:03.280 --> 00:07:08.800
are, what they're doing, how they download
apps, where they download apps, and how they

00:07:08.800 --> 00:07:10.480
consume and use those applications.

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:13.240
And, really, it's a lot simpler than would
you think.

00:07:13.240 --> 00:07:14.450
People always think, oh, research.

00:07:14.450 --> 00:07:18.720
They think about IDC or they think about Nielsen
or they think about tens of thousand of dollars

00:07:18.720 --> 00:07:20.120
spent on research.

00:07:20.120 --> 00:07:23.840
It's really not that complex or that expensive.

00:07:23.840 --> 00:07:28.150
The way we break it down, for example, is
we look at quantitative versus qualitative

00:07:28.150 --> 00:07:29.150
research.

00:07:29.150 --> 00:07:34.620
At its very basic level, your quantitative
research is basically when you go out and

00:07:34.620 --> 00:07:40.370
you do extensive questionnaires and you survey
thousands of different consumers or hundreds

00:07:40.370 --> 00:07:41.370
of different consumers.

00:07:41.370 --> 00:07:45.160
And you're asking the basic questions that
you're trying to get answered.

00:07:45.160 --> 00:07:48.620
How often does this consumer download applications?

00:07:48.620 --> 00:07:51.110
What kind of handsets are they using?

00:07:51.110 --> 00:07:54.370
How much per month are they spending downloading
applications?

00:07:54.370 --> 00:07:57.150
How long are they spending in an application
session?

00:07:57.150 --> 00:08:02.030
You're really trying to understand kind of
the macro, broad picture of consumer demographics

00:08:02.030 --> 00:08:06.610
and habits and consumption to guide the development
philosophy for your application.

00:08:06.610 --> 00:08:11.470
Then, of course, as you start building your
application, you get near that famous milestone,

00:08:11.470 --> 00:08:16.910
that first milestone of having a beta or an
alpha, then, really, it's about qualitative

00:08:16.910 --> 00:08:18.250
research.

00:08:18.250 --> 00:08:22.720
And qualitative research can take a lot of
different forms, like focus groups, for example.

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:26.240
Or screen focus groups, or just sitting down
with a bunch of people that you may or may

00:08:26.240 --> 00:08:30.320
not know that well around pizza and beers
and trying to understand what they think of

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:31.380
your app.

00:08:31.380 --> 00:08:35.210
And this is really the in-depth part of the
market research, which is where you're really

00:08:35.210 --> 00:08:38.770
trying to understand how's the consumer using
my app?

00:08:38.770 --> 00:08:40.490
How quickly does my app load?

00:08:40.490 --> 00:08:42.580
What kind of features do they like?

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:45.000
How easy is the UI to navigate?

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:47.330
And what kind of features could enhance the
application?

00:08:47.330 --> 00:08:52.270
Or better yet, what features should I remove
because the consumers simply don't either

00:08:52.270 --> 00:08:55.810
get the features or they don't really use
the features?

00:08:55.810 --> 00:09:01.140
The best news about research and its ability
to guide our development philosophy, as I

00:09:01.140 --> 00:09:05.080
said earlier, is that it's neither that expensive
or that time-consuming.

00:09:05.080 --> 00:09:08.050
You can start right now and you can do research
online.

00:09:08.050 --> 00:09:12.920
You can go, for example, to google.com/insights,
put together three simple questions, survey

00:09:12.920 --> 00:09:18.490
1500 consumers and get answers in three to
four days at less than $1,000.

00:09:18.490 --> 00:09:21.070
On the quantitative side.

00:09:21.070 --> 00:09:24.500
And your focus groups -- again, this is something
you just need to know enough people that you

00:09:24.500 --> 00:09:29.260
can get together groups of people and spend
an afternoon brainstorming and getting feedback.

00:09:29.260 --> 00:09:34.880
It's really not that hard and there's a lot
of tools available to do that.

00:09:34.880 --> 00:09:38.690
And now introducing the real four Ps.

00:09:38.690 --> 00:09:43.880
So how did the real four Ps influence our
marketing and our thinking around app marketing?

00:09:43.880 --> 00:09:47.740
Well, of course, when we talk about the real
four Ps, we're talking about product, which

00:09:47.740 --> 00:09:49.060
is our app.

00:09:49.060 --> 00:09:52.860
We're talking about price, which is our business
model.

00:09:52.860 --> 00:09:59.140
We're talking about distribution, which ends
up being how many devices are we covering?

00:09:59.140 --> 00:10:01.820
What operating systems are we developing on?

00:10:01.820 --> 00:10:05.260
And what channels within those operating systems
are we distributing on?

00:10:05.260 --> 00:10:09.750
And lastly, we're talking about promotions,
which can be anything from the type of assets

00:10:09.750 --> 00:10:15.230
that we build, the thumbnails, the screen
shots, the assets, the videos, our banners,

00:10:15.230 --> 00:10:21.170
search ads, all the kind of tools that we
would use to promote our applications.

00:10:21.170 --> 00:10:26.620
So talking about product, and I love this
analogy, and it's actually even better to

00:10:26.620 --> 00:10:30.090
use this analogy at 4:00 in the afternoon,
because by that point, I know most of you

00:10:30.090 --> 00:10:33.940
people have eaten, so you're not starving,
and you won't just run out of the room when

00:10:33.940 --> 00:10:36.260
you see all this stuff that's on the slide.

00:10:36.260 --> 00:10:41.150
But truth be told, the way I look at it is
it's about snacking versus feasting.

00:10:41.150 --> 00:10:42.590
Right?

00:10:42.590 --> 00:10:46.470
So around 4:00 or 5:00 in the afternoon, like
right now, you might have a little hunger.

00:10:46.470 --> 00:10:49.220
You might want a little something to snack
on.

00:10:49.220 --> 00:10:54.270
So you grab, you know, a Snickers bar or you'll
grab a bag of chips.

00:10:54.270 --> 00:10:58.120
And you open that bag of chips, and you will
push your hand into the bag, and you will

00:10:58.120 --> 00:10:59.270
take out one or two chips.

00:10:59.270 --> 00:11:02.550
But you're not going to put your hand in and
take all the chips out of the bag and stuff

00:11:02.550 --> 00:11:03.550
them in your face.

00:11:03.550 --> 00:11:06.650
Well, some people might, but you probably
won't.

00:11:06.650 --> 00:11:10.460
It's really something that you do just to
kill the hunger at that particular point in

00:11:10.460 --> 00:11:15.630
time, versus, of course, feasting, which is
what's going to happen around 11:00 or midnight

00:11:15.630 --> 00:11:19.960
tonight after you've been hearing Paul Oakenfold
and you're starving and you need about five

00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:21.020
courses.

00:11:21.020 --> 00:11:24.160
Totally different experience.

00:11:24.160 --> 00:11:27.590
Why am I using this example?

00:11:27.590 --> 00:11:34.570
Mobile app usage and mobile app consumption
is all about snacking.

00:11:34.570 --> 00:11:37.110
It's not about feasting.

00:11:37.110 --> 00:11:41.860
If you look at the research, the research
that we see and the research that's publicly

00:11:41.860 --> 00:11:46.580
available will tell you that on average, consumers
are spending probably around an hour and a

00:11:46.580 --> 00:11:49.700
half per day using apps.

00:11:49.700 --> 00:11:51.480
So what does that tell us?

00:11:51.480 --> 00:11:56.330
Well, that tells us that if they're spending
about an hour and a half per day using apps,

00:11:56.330 --> 00:12:01.390
and they've got maybe 30 apps on their phone,
of which they use ten frequently, well, they're

00:12:01.390 --> 00:12:04.460
probably going to use your app no more than
nine or ten minutes a day.

00:12:04.460 --> 00:12:06.460
Sounds obvious.

00:12:06.460 --> 00:12:10.090
But what's the implication for product development?

00:12:10.090 --> 00:12:11.970
There's a couple of implications.

00:12:11.970 --> 00:12:16.010
The first implication is that if I'm -- as
a consumer, I'm using my favorite app, and

00:12:16.010 --> 00:12:20.180
I'm using it for five minutes a day, if I
get a notification from you that says that

00:12:20.180 --> 00:12:25.410
I need to update my application, activate
my Wi-Fi, and download two gigabytes of files

00:12:25.410 --> 00:12:29.900
-- well, maybe with smart apps, now that's
going to be easier.

00:12:29.900 --> 00:12:32.220
But that still kind of goes against the philosophy
of snacking.

00:12:32.220 --> 00:12:37.760
Why am I going to spend five minutes downloading
a file when I'm using the app maybe nine minutes

00:12:37.760 --> 00:12:39.640
every single day?

00:12:39.640 --> 00:12:42.970
It has implications in terms of the load speed;
right?

00:12:42.970 --> 00:12:47.560
If I'm getting on a bus and I've got two stops
and I want to check my sports scores or I

00:12:47.560 --> 00:12:50.980
want to see what the weather's like in London
-- we know what the weather's like in London

00:12:50.980 --> 00:12:56.540
-- but if I want to see what the weather is
like in London, I don't want the application

00:12:56.540 --> 00:12:59.700
to take 20 to 30 seconds to load.

00:12:59.700 --> 00:13:02.901
I want to dip my hand into the experience,
dip it out, get my information, thank you

00:13:02.901 --> 00:13:05.270
very much, and I'm done.

00:13:05.270 --> 00:13:07.280
And it has lots of other implications as well.

00:13:07.280 --> 00:13:08.280
Right?

00:13:08.280 --> 00:13:13.020
It has implications in terms of how easy is
the application to use.

00:13:13.020 --> 00:13:17.630
Let's say that I am on that bus in London
and I've got about 15 minutes' commute.

00:13:17.630 --> 00:13:22.410
Well, am I going to spend five minutes of
those 15 minutes actually reading through

00:13:22.410 --> 00:13:26.350
all, like, you know, the options that are
available in the app and trying to read and

00:13:26.350 --> 00:13:28.360
understand how the app works?

00:13:28.360 --> 00:13:29.360
Probably not.

00:13:29.360 --> 00:13:34.010
I really want to get into the experience quickly,
which means I need an intuitive UI, I need

00:13:34.010 --> 00:13:39.000
very easy-to-use features, I need to be able
to dip in and dip out very quickly.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:43.130
So understanding your users and understanding
that people snack has direct implications

00:13:43.130 --> 00:13:46.540
for how you develop content.

00:13:46.540 --> 00:13:49.500
So let's talk for a minute about great applications.

00:13:49.500 --> 00:13:51.270
And there are thousands of great applications.

00:13:51.270 --> 00:13:53.400
And, of course, we can't possibly cite them
all.

00:13:53.400 --> 00:13:56.730
But this is an old-school example that I like
to use.

00:13:56.730 --> 00:14:02.440
eBuddy is a Dutch developer that's been around
since 2005, 2006, started originally developing

00:14:02.440 --> 00:14:04.130
J2ME apps.

00:14:04.130 --> 00:14:09.890
I remember that fondly, because I started
my career in games trying to sell J2ME games

00:14:09.890 --> 00:14:12.120
to carriers five years ago.

00:14:12.120 --> 00:14:14.730
And hence the first slide about please, please,
please.

00:14:14.730 --> 00:14:17.700
You probably get the rest of the picture.

00:14:17.700 --> 00:14:22.120
Needless to say, obviously, you know, these
guys have been around a very long time.

00:14:22.120 --> 00:14:25.300
And they do a lot of things really, really
well.

00:14:25.300 --> 00:14:27.950
So what we did was we put together a handy
little checklist together for these guys for

00:14:27.950 --> 00:14:30.339
what we think they do well.

00:14:30.339 --> 00:14:33.589
A couple of things.

00:14:33.589 --> 00:14:37.620
First of all, the product really solves a
clear and present need.

00:14:37.620 --> 00:14:42.430
As I mentioned earlier, at the beginning of
my speech, you're either entertaining or you're

00:14:42.430 --> 00:14:46.350
addressing a specific issue or making the
person's life easier.

00:14:46.350 --> 00:14:51.921
eBuddy does that basically by aggregating
five or six different IMs into one easy to

00:14:51.921 --> 00:14:55.370
use client where you can be logged into all
your instant messengers and be chatting with

00:14:55.370 --> 00:14:58.810
your friends anywhere in the world no matter
what instant messenger they're using.

00:14:58.810 --> 00:15:01.750
They saw the need.

00:15:01.750 --> 00:15:04.080
They had excellent device coverage.

00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:09.620
One of the things that amazes me about developers
is that sometimes we'll see these great apps,

00:15:09.620 --> 00:15:16.280
and they'll be, like, 500 megabytes in size
and have a black list of 1200 devices.

00:15:16.280 --> 00:15:23.150
Well, one of the ways that you basically get
noticed in the apps market is through virality.

00:15:23.150 --> 00:15:24.740
And virality means reach.

00:15:24.740 --> 00:15:27.279
And reach means device coverage.

00:15:27.279 --> 00:15:32.120
These guys have a very simple app that works
very quickly, it's easy to use, it loads quickly,

00:15:32.120 --> 00:15:36.470
the UI is super intuitive and they're available
across lots of different devices.

00:15:36.470 --> 00:15:41.740
As a matter of fact, they're available on
nearly every device from Android 1.5 and up.

00:15:41.740 --> 00:15:44.830
Now, I'm not telling you guys need to go back
and develop on 1.5.

00:15:44.830 --> 00:15:51.000
But what I'm saying is, you need to be available
on as many devices as are relevant to maximize

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:53.810
your virality.

00:15:53.810 --> 00:15:57.170
Of course, the other thing that's important
with this application which goes without saying

00:15:57.170 --> 00:16:02.670
and also helps virality is parity of features
across operating systems.

00:16:02.670 --> 00:16:07.000
If I have a great application that I get on
Android and it's got these cool features and

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:10.110
I tell my friend about it and he's got an
iPhone, he goes out and downloads it and it

00:16:10.110 --> 00:16:14.029
doesn't have the same features, that's kind
of a crummy experience for him.

00:16:14.029 --> 00:16:15.120
Right?

00:16:15.120 --> 00:16:20.540
Likewise, if the opposite happens that somebody
gets a great application on iOS and then tells

00:16:20.540 --> 00:16:24.280
their friend and their friend downloads the
Android version and it's a port, that's not

00:16:24.280 --> 00:16:26.390
a really cool thing to do, either.

00:16:26.390 --> 00:16:29.589
And, as a matter of fact, when you talk about
placement and getting featured in the Google

00:16:29.589 --> 00:16:34.860
Play Store, that is a sure way not to get
featured in the Play Store.

00:16:34.860 --> 00:16:35.940
Right?

00:16:35.940 --> 00:16:40.000
We want to make sure that Android consumers
have the best possible experience, and, if

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:43.490
possible, a better experience than on other
platforms.

00:16:43.490 --> 00:16:48.290
And lastly, continuously upgrading the application,
making sure that you're constantly fixing

00:16:48.290 --> 00:16:53.670
bugs, constantly removing features that are
out of date, constantly improving on new features,

00:16:53.670 --> 00:16:58.210
and making sure that the quality of your application
isn't just good when you launch, but it's

00:16:58.210 --> 00:17:02.000
continuously and consistently good across
all your revisions.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:10.470
And if you look at eBuddy, they have a 4.3
rating across 155,000 reviews.

00:17:10.470 --> 00:17:16.050
And they have done 10 to 50 million downloads
on Google Play, which is actually a lot more

00:17:16.050 --> 00:17:19.939
than some of the better-known apps than we
know here in the Valley.

00:17:19.939 --> 00:17:24.040
So a lot of different things to (indiscernible)
over on our checklist.

00:17:24.040 --> 00:17:28.860
So you've heard a lot with productive from
me, but I'd like to turn it over to a video

00:17:28.860 --> 00:17:34.320
from one of our top developers to talk about
their experience on product.

