]
&gt;&gt;Patrick Mork: Great.

00:19:59.810 --> 00:20:01.700
So there you have a little bit from Storm8.

00:20:01.700 --> 00:20:06.880
But as I hope you noticed, research, rigorous
development process, really iterating and

00:20:06.880 --> 00:20:10.210
really understanding the data, right, critical
to getting the product right.

00:20:10.210 --> 00:20:15.780
But, of course, although we like to make great
apps and games, you know, if we can't pay

00:20:15.780 --> 00:20:20.090
the water bill at the end of the month, it
all becomes a little bit hairy; right?

00:20:20.090 --> 00:20:23.799
So no conversation would be complete, you
know, without talking about business models.

00:20:23.799 --> 00:20:26.550
I'm not going to spend a lot of time here,
because, of course, many of you just sat through

00:20:26.550 --> 00:20:30.950
a session on monetization with Kenneth Lui
and his colleagues.

00:20:30.950 --> 00:20:34.100
I think they did an excellent job of describing
the various models out there.

00:20:34.100 --> 00:20:37.910
What I will try and do is add a little bit
my two cents and experience based on how to

00:20:37.910 --> 00:20:41.650
look at each one of these individual models
and some of the unique variables that affect

00:20:41.650 --> 00:20:42.650
each.

00:20:42.650 --> 00:20:45.980
So, you know, you've heard about freemium,
you've heard about the march of freemium and

00:20:45.980 --> 00:20:47.250
how well that's doing.

00:20:47.250 --> 00:20:51.150
As Chris mentioned, it's over 50% of our revenue
now which is exciting.

00:20:51.150 --> 00:20:55.059
And we've seen a huge takeoff in freemium
over the last months.

00:20:55.059 --> 00:20:57.980
That's not to say that it's the right model
for you.

00:20:57.980 --> 00:21:00.940
That's not to say that it's going to make
you super competitive against the other apps

00:21:00.940 --> 00:21:02.350
on your system.

00:21:02.350 --> 00:21:05.920
As we see, freemium works better in some categories
versus others.

00:21:05.920 --> 00:21:10.290
We really have to understand what the right
price points are when it comes to freemium.

00:21:10.290 --> 00:21:12.870
What's going to be the way to engage with
consumers?

00:21:12.870 --> 00:21:15.590
How often do we provide notifications to consumers?

00:21:15.590 --> 00:21:19.200
What kind of notifications do we provide and
at what price points?

00:21:19.200 --> 00:21:24.960
So it's really about testing, testing, re-understanding,
changing the pricing, looking at price elasticity,

00:21:24.960 --> 00:21:28.530
and really measuring and analyzing what works.

00:21:28.530 --> 00:21:32.590
More importantly, I think one of the questions
I want to address directly is talked about

00:21:32.590 --> 00:21:33.640
paid applications.

00:21:33.640 --> 00:21:36.510
Because many of your applications out there
will still be paid apps.

00:21:36.510 --> 00:21:39.640
And as mentioned earlier, freemium might not
work for you.

00:21:39.640 --> 00:21:43.299
So let's spend a minute talking about paid
applications.

00:21:43.299 --> 00:21:46.960
And I really wanted to talk about two things
when it has to do with paid apps.

00:21:46.960 --> 00:21:51.430
Because even though we're in the world of
smartphones and Java is long gone from now,

00:21:51.430 --> 00:21:54.160
well, there's still a lot of things that don't
change.

00:21:54.160 --> 00:21:56.690
There's still a lot of constants that remain
the same.

00:21:56.690 --> 00:22:00.150
One of those is the challenge around pricing.

00:22:00.150 --> 00:22:05.220
So the myth around the 99-cent price point
or the 99-cent dilemma as I call it, here's

00:22:05.220 --> 00:22:10.530
the dilemma: The dilemma is that if you look
at a curve and you look at the number of applications

00:22:10.530 --> 00:22:15.000
available on the Android platform or on iOS
for that matter, you'll see the left side

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:20.050
of the curve where the majority of the apps
lie are where most of those apps are at 99

00:22:20.050 --> 00:22:21.050
cents.

00:22:21.050 --> 00:22:22.790
And here's the problem with that.

00:22:22.790 --> 00:22:30.700
Well, the problem is that if you price your
app at 99 cents from the get-go, how do you

00:22:30.700 --> 00:22:31.710
discount?

00:22:31.710 --> 00:22:37.230
If you want to put your app on sale, where
do you go from 99 cents?

00:22:37.230 --> 00:22:38.230
You can't.

00:22:38.230 --> 00:22:40.420
It's a lot harder.

00:22:40.420 --> 00:22:44.980
And one of the rules of marketing, you'll
hear several of those today, is very simple,

00:22:44.980 --> 00:22:53.160
and it's this: It's always a lot easier to
take your price down than to raise your price.

00:22:53.160 --> 00:22:58.830
In any product, in any category, in any supermarket,
in any industry, it's always the same case.

00:22:58.830 --> 00:23:02.300
So our recommendation there is, if you are
going to have paid apps, always start at a

00:23:02.300 --> 00:23:06.180
slightly higher price point, because it gives
you flexibility to discount and make offers

00:23:06.180 --> 00:23:08.179
on your application.

00:23:08.179 --> 00:23:13.179
The other reason why we believe pricing at
99 cents is a risk is because, ultimately,

00:23:13.179 --> 00:23:16.500
most of us, when we go to make a purchase,
let's say we're buying a pair of sneakers

00:23:16.500 --> 00:23:23.040
or buying a pair of jeans or we're buying,
I don't know, a plane ticket, having a lower

00:23:23.040 --> 00:23:26.410
price tells us a certain thing about the product
that we're buying.

00:23:26.410 --> 00:23:30.510
And in many cases, low price equals cheap.

00:23:30.510 --> 00:23:34.130
So the question to you, then, is, is that
the kind of message that you want to pass

00:23:34.130 --> 00:23:35.200
to your consumer?

00:23:35.200 --> 00:23:37.370
The person that's seeing your app for the
first time?

00:23:37.370 --> 00:23:41.410
That maybe sees your app side by side with
five other competitors, and you're the cheapest

00:23:41.410 --> 00:23:43.320
app?

00:23:43.320 --> 00:23:45.940
That sometimes works for consumers who are
really price-sensitive.

00:23:45.940 --> 00:23:49.970
But for other consumers, they'll look at that
and say, "This app basically does the same,

00:23:49.970 --> 00:23:52.100
so it's probably not as good."

00:23:52.100 --> 00:23:54.260
And that does happen.

00:23:54.260 --> 00:23:57.910
More likely what we like to did is we like
to encourage you guys to really think about

00:23:57.910 --> 00:24:00.430
the price life cycle of your application.

00:24:00.430 --> 00:24:03.940
What we've done is build kind of a theoretical
model on what that looks like.

00:24:03.940 --> 00:24:09.520
In this particular case, an app developer
launches an app or game at 2.99 and they get

00:24:09.520 --> 00:24:10.880
a certain number of installs.

00:24:10.880 --> 00:24:12.179
The first month, it's 50,000.

00:24:12.179 --> 00:24:13.980
The second month, it's another 40,000.

00:24:13.980 --> 00:24:16.100
The third month, it starts to drop.

00:24:16.100 --> 00:24:21.070
And at that point, because they priced at
2.99, they're able to able to drop the price.

00:24:21.070 --> 00:24:26.540
So they drop the price to 1.99, and they get
a whole bunch of new users who go, "Oh, yes,

00:24:26.540 --> 00:24:27.540
great.

00:24:27.540 --> 00:24:28.540
An offer.

00:24:28.540 --> 00:24:29.540
I'm going to get this app now."

00:24:29.540 --> 00:24:31.720
And they share with their friends, and they
say, "You know, I was a cheap bastard before.

00:24:31.720 --> 00:24:32.720
I didn't want to buy it at $3.

00:24:32.720 --> 00:24:34.200
But now it's at 2.

00:24:34.200 --> 00:24:35.200
I'm in."

00:24:35.200 --> 00:24:36.200
So they buy the app.

00:24:36.200 --> 00:24:40.090
And the friends start piling in and you get
a little bit of virality because they're getting

00:24:40.090 --> 00:24:41.090
a great deal.

00:24:41.090 --> 00:24:42.650
What do you do?

00:24:42.650 --> 00:24:43.950
You raise the price.

00:24:43.950 --> 00:24:48.110
Once you start getting that volume build and
that momentum, you raise the price.

00:24:48.110 --> 00:24:51.740
A lot of consumers who may have heard about
how great your app was, they don't necessarily

00:24:51.740 --> 00:24:56.000
realize the price is no longer discounted,
so they still buy it.

00:24:56.000 --> 00:25:00.470
And you can basically get the difference of
what you were charging before versus after.

00:25:00.470 --> 00:25:05.140
And you can do that in cycles over time, until
you get to the end of the life cycle, or maybe

00:25:05.140 --> 00:25:09.340
12 months or eight months out or whatever
your product plan is, you decide you're going

00:25:09.340 --> 00:25:12.580
to phase out that app and launch a completely
new one.

00:25:12.580 --> 00:25:17.390
What do you do, since you priced at 2.99,
you're going to drop the price to 99 cents,

00:25:17.390 --> 00:25:19.830
that's a great bargain.

00:25:19.830 --> 00:25:23.410
You can do that because you're at the end
of your price cycle and you're going to introduce

00:25:23.410 --> 00:25:26.110
another app anyway.

00:25:26.110 --> 00:25:30.730
There what I'm saying is theoretical model
but encourage you to think of what is the

00:25:30.730 --> 00:25:35.370
price life cycle of my app, how do I manage
it over a time and how do I give myself enough

00:25:35.370 --> 00:25:40.880
flexibility with my price point that I can
move and pivot and change my price if I have

00:25:40.880 --> 00:25:41.880
to?

00:25:41.880 --> 00:25:45.560
Let's talk about ads.

00:25:45.560 --> 00:25:49.270
So this chart was taken from a Kleiner Perkins
presentation by Mary Meeker.

00:25:49.270 --> 00:25:54.900
Some of you guys may read Mary Meeker on occasion
when she publishes material on the Internet

00:25:54.900 --> 00:25:58.010
specifically and about mobile Internet.

00:25:58.010 --> 00:26:03.580
And the thing about ads is this: There's some
good news and there's some opportunistic news;

00:26:03.580 --> 00:26:04.580
right?

00:26:04.580 --> 00:26:09.040
The reality about ads is that ads today in
terms of ECPMs, which is the effective cost

00:26:09.040 --> 00:26:14.680
per thousand or what you're getting paid for
your ads, is the ECPMs on mobile are significantly

00:26:14.680 --> 00:26:15.750
lower than on desktop.

00:26:15.750 --> 00:26:17.200
No surprise; right?

00:26:17.200 --> 00:26:20.090
Desktop's been around ten years, has a different
user base.

00:26:20.090 --> 00:26:24.190
They spend perhaps more time on desktop, so
the value of ECPM is higher.

00:26:24.190 --> 00:26:26.510
Mobile is still a lot lower.

00:26:26.510 --> 00:26:29.592
But the good news is, when you look at this
graph, you'll see that the yellow bar, the

00:26:29.592 --> 00:26:34.880
bar on the left across all of these different
types of media, that's the amount of time

00:26:34.880 --> 00:26:36.960
spent by consumers.

00:26:36.960 --> 00:26:38.170
So what do we see here?

00:26:38.170 --> 00:26:42.450
Well, we see that on average, consumers are
spending about 10% of their time on mobile,

00:26:42.450 --> 00:26:43.900
which is huge.

00:26:43.900 --> 00:26:47.610
That's massively encouraging for every single
one of us in this room and every single one

00:26:47.610 --> 00:26:50.600
of us around the world who is developing great
content.

00:26:50.600 --> 00:26:56.480
The challenge is, only 1% of the ad dollars
are flowing into mobile today.

00:26:56.480 --> 00:26:59.179
But that means a massive opportunity.

00:26:59.179 --> 00:27:00.799
Why?

00:27:00.799 --> 00:27:02.419
Simple.

00:27:02.419 --> 00:27:06.820
Dollars always follow eyeballs.

00:27:06.820 --> 00:27:08.590
That's just the way advertising works.

00:27:08.590 --> 00:27:09.810
There's always a lag.

00:27:09.810 --> 00:27:13.290
Which means, essentially, if you have a great
product and you really understand how to monetize

00:27:13.290 --> 00:27:18.840
through ads, it's a question of time before
that gap closes and before the ECPMs either

00:27:18.840 --> 00:27:23.299
get close to or match what we see on desktops
and enable you guys to really maximize the

00:27:23.299 --> 00:27:28.039
monetization of your apps through ads.

00:27:28.039 --> 00:27:31.370
I think the last point I want to make -- well,
two more points on monetization before moving

00:27:31.370 --> 00:27:35.310
on -- is, use hybrids.

00:27:35.310 --> 00:27:36.310
We saw that earlier.

00:27:36.310 --> 00:27:38.110
We talked -- we saw paymium.

00:27:38.110 --> 00:27:40.180
We saw a combination of different business
models.

00:27:40.180 --> 00:27:44.130
And this is really exciting stuff because
what we're seeing is more and more developers

00:27:44.130 --> 00:27:47.160
are starting to do that and it's starting
to pay dividends.

00:27:47.160 --> 00:27:50.200
And it also reduces your risk as a developer.

00:27:50.200 --> 00:27:51.900
So if you have in-app payments, that's great.

00:27:51.900 --> 00:27:55.669
Why not throw in app ads if it makes sense,
and you can potentially monetize from both

00:27:55.669 --> 00:27:58.270
or you can see which works better than the
other.

00:27:58.270 --> 00:28:02.320
Having a hybrid and a combination of different
business models gives you more flexibility

00:28:02.320 --> 00:28:05.790
and maximizes your ability to monetize your
apps.

00:28:05.790 --> 00:28:09.070
Last point on monetization.

00:28:09.070 --> 00:28:13.480
We live in a global world.

00:28:13.480 --> 00:28:17.919
Apps are being downloaded every single second,
all over the world, on all sorts of different

00:28:17.919 --> 00:28:18.919
devices.

00:28:18.919 --> 00:28:21.929
So what are the implications for you as app
developers?

00:28:21.929 --> 00:28:22.929
Simple.

00:28:22.929 --> 00:28:28.760
Different business models will work differently
in different countries.

00:28:28.760 --> 00:28:32.179
So if you've got a great game in the United
States where you know that a lot of consumers,

00:28:32.179 --> 00:28:38.110
may be 60% plus of consumers are on contract
and have higher-end smartphones, chances are

00:28:38.110 --> 00:28:43.900
those consumers are more willing to pay for
your app, therefore, a paid app or in-app

00:28:43.900 --> 00:28:46.940
payments might make more sense for you.

00:28:46.940 --> 00:28:52.090
But if you're trying to distribute and monetize
your apps in India, where, potentially, 90

00:28:52.090 --> 00:28:58.040
to 95% of consumers are on prepaid cards and
they're still in the process of rolling out

00:28:58.040 --> 00:29:03.120
3G networks where data is expensive, then
perhaps that business model doesn't work as

00:29:03.120 --> 00:29:07.790
well and you need to think of maybe I should
monetize through ads.

00:29:07.790 --> 00:29:12.590
The reality there is, try and look at your
market globally and see how you can monetize

00:29:12.590 --> 00:29:16.130
your app using different business models in
different regions.

00:29:16.130 --> 00:29:18.690
Be creative.

00:29:18.690 --> 00:29:21.820
So once we've built this great product and
we know how we're going to monetize it and

00:29:21.820 --> 00:29:26.169
keep all the lights on at the end of the day,
well, then we start thinking about, aha, how

00:29:26.169 --> 00:29:28.049
do I promote my app?

00:29:28.049 --> 00:29:29.640
Where should I spend my money?

00:29:29.640 --> 00:29:33.080
Where should I spend those hard-earned VC
dollars that are going to enable me to get

00:29:33.080 --> 00:29:44.520
more users, yay, another rule of marketing,
rule number two numero uno, don't invest behind

00:29:44.520 --> 00:29:46.860
a weak product.

00:29:46.860 --> 00:29:48.470
It goes behind saying.

00:29:48.470 --> 00:29:53.100
But you see people do this all the time, and
not just in our business, but in tons of businesses.

00:29:53.100 --> 00:29:58.169
If you invest behind a weak product, you're
basically creating a negative consumer perception

00:29:58.169 --> 00:30:02.100
of your product and of your brand, if that's
what you're trying to build.

00:30:02.100 --> 00:30:05.480
You should go back to the drawing board and
rework your application until you're sure

00:30:05.480 --> 00:30:08.120
that you have the best possible experience.

00:30:08.120 --> 00:30:11.640
If you're not excited about your application
or you're not convinced you would pay, do

00:30:11.640 --> 00:30:14.860
you think a consumer is because they're going
to see an ad that you're seeing on AdMob or

00:30:14.860 --> 00:30:16.570
somewhere else?

00:30:16.570 --> 00:30:18.770
Probably not.

00:30:18.770 --> 00:30:22.340
Once you're really sure that you have a great
product, then there's a number of great frameworks

00:30:22.340 --> 00:30:26.940
we can suggest to you that are going to help
you put together your marketing plan.

00:30:26.940 --> 00:30:29.049
The first of these is STP.

00:30:29.049 --> 00:30:30.049
Knowing your users.

00:30:30.049 --> 00:30:36.120
It's all about segmenting, targeting, and
then positioning your app properly.

00:30:36.120 --> 00:30:40.760
The second one is once I position my app properly,
I know who I'm going after, what's the message

00:30:40.760 --> 00:30:43.030
I'm giving the consumer?

00:30:43.030 --> 00:30:44.570
What is my one liner?

00:30:44.570 --> 00:30:46.169
What are my points of difference?

00:30:46.169 --> 00:30:48.020
Why should a consumer care?

00:30:48.020 --> 00:30:52.070
Third, once I have all my messaging down and
I've properly positioned my app and I know

00:30:52.070 --> 00:30:56.070
where I'm going, it's, well, how do I build
a structured marketing plan?

00:30:56.070 --> 00:30:57.630
What needs to go into my marking plan?

00:30:57.630 --> 00:30:59.080
What kind of activity should I do?

00:30:59.080 --> 00:31:03.080
Lastly, what is my media strategy look like.

00:31:03.080 --> 00:31:06.520
The good news is I'm going to go through each
one of these in detail and explain in detail

00:31:06.520 --> 00:31:09.809
a little more clearly.

00:31:09.809 --> 00:31:12.020
Let's look at our audience.

00:31:12.020 --> 00:31:18.330
So let's say, for example, I'm a game developer
and I've seen this great case study from Kenneth

00:31:18.330 --> 00:31:23.450
Lui at Google I/O, I've decided, you know
what, that's it, dude, I'm going for in-app

00:31:23.450 --> 00:31:24.780
payments.

00:31:24.780 --> 00:31:28.990
I'm going to do in-app payments with, like,
funky furry animals at different price points.

00:31:28.990 --> 00:31:33.080
I'm going to get a ton of downloads to get
consumers to basically pay me a the lot of

00:31:33.080 --> 00:31:35.710
money.

00:31:35.710 --> 00:31:39.159
If you are going to do in-app payments on
games, then probably what you need to do is

00:31:39.159 --> 00:31:47.150
really segment your target audience properly
and look at how you target those people.

00:31:47.150 --> 00:31:53.350
Excuse me.

00:31:53.350 --> 00:31:56.740
So if I'm using in-app payments for game,
there's two axis probably that I'm going to

00:31:56.740 --> 00:31:57.740
look at.

00:31:57.740 --> 00:31:59.460
I'm going to look at available time.

00:31:59.460 --> 00:32:01.679
I need people to have available time to play
my games.

00:32:01.679 --> 00:32:04.310
And then I'm probably going to look at disposable
income.

00:32:04.310 --> 00:32:08.970
Because if a person is 13 years old and has
tons of available time but no income, I'm

00:32:08.970 --> 00:32:11.600
not going to make much money from them.

00:32:11.600 --> 00:32:14.159
I segment my audience this way.

00:32:14.159 --> 00:32:16.549
I come up with all these different segments
that I have.

00:32:16.549 --> 00:32:23.230
Upscale adults, techies, middle income families,
soccer moms, whatever it happens to be.

00:32:23.230 --> 00:32:28.120
And when I look at my matrix, I think, okay,
the right target audience is probably these

00:32:28.120 --> 00:32:29.120
guys.

00:32:29.120 --> 00:32:34.410
Young adults 24-35 years old, no kids, right?

00:32:34.410 --> 00:32:37.299
So they have disposable time and they have
income.

00:32:37.299 --> 00:32:38.299
That's my target audience.

00:32:38.299 --> 00:32:41.860
Then it's a question of, okay, how do I position
my app?

00:32:41.860 --> 00:32:43.390
What's my one-liner to those people?

00:32:43.390 --> 00:32:49.090
What am I going to tell those people to click
and install my application?

00:32:49.090 --> 00:32:51.110
Which takes us to the next step.

00:32:51.110 --> 00:32:54.570
How do I develop convincing messaging?

00:32:54.570 --> 00:32:58.800
What's the one line that I'm going to tell
people about my sports application that is

00:32:58.800 --> 00:33:01.850
going to get them so excited that they are
going to want to download it?

00:33:01.850 --> 00:33:05.030
Is it that I have realtime instantaneous scores?

00:33:05.030 --> 00:33:09.210
Is it the fact that I'm the only application
that has social engagement and built-in hangouts

00:33:09.210 --> 00:33:10.740
into it?

00:33:10.740 --> 00:33:13.870
Is it the fact that I have this application
that runs on all sorts of different platforms

00:33:13.870 --> 00:33:16.059
and backs up my data on the web?

00:33:16.059 --> 00:33:17.210
What's your one liner?

00:33:17.210 --> 00:33:19.679
What's your positioning statement?

00:33:19.679 --> 00:33:23.350
After that, what are the two or three key
points of difference that are going to go

00:33:23.350 --> 00:33:24.850
into my product description?

00:33:24.850 --> 00:33:29.520
So that when people land on my page, because
they have searched or clicked an ad, they

00:33:29.520 --> 00:33:31.890
read these three or four great things about
the application.

00:33:31.890 --> 00:33:35.200
Not the bug fixes, but the stuff that really
matters.

00:33:35.200 --> 00:33:40.110
They think, this app is really cool because
it has Android beam and I can do all this

00:33:40.110 --> 00:33:44.530
crazy stuff like play multiplayer games without
activating Bluetooth or Wi-Fi.

00:33:44.530 --> 00:33:45.530
That's wicked cool.

00:33:45.530 --> 00:33:48.950
I'm going to get that instead of that other
application.

00:33:48.950 --> 00:33:51.679
And lastly, what's my call to action?

00:33:51.679 --> 00:33:59.100
When you start doing Get Creative, we see
app developers do ad campaigns, online stuff,

00:33:59.100 --> 00:34:03.470
banners, they advertise their little logo
with a little dragon and it doesn't tell me

00:34:03.470 --> 00:34:06.650
anything about what I should do next.

00:34:06.650 --> 00:34:12.029
Okay, so you've got me all excited about your
little furry animals and I can get these collectable

00:34:12.029 --> 00:34:13.779
items, what do I do?

00:34:13.779 --> 00:34:15.319
Where do I go?

00:34:15.319 --> 00:34:17.809
Where can I find this app?

00:34:17.809 --> 00:34:19.269
Clear calls to action.

00:34:19.269 --> 00:34:22.579
On the right-hand side -- actually I thought
it would be fun to share this.

00:34:22.579 --> 00:34:29.119
Kushagra, who is working with us right here
on the Google Play team and actually is the

00:34:29.119 --> 00:34:32.440
one who really was responsible for a lot of
this material as well as the interviews, so

00:34:32.440 --> 00:34:34.960
I owe him a huge debt of gratitude on that.

00:34:34.960 --> 00:34:40.929
Kushagra put together an amazing promotion
at the end of last year around apps.

00:34:40.929 --> 00:34:42.049
Some of you guys may have seen it.

00:34:42.049 --> 00:34:44.499
In December, we hit 10 billion downloads.

00:34:44.499 --> 00:34:46.210
We did a promotion called 10-10-10.

00:34:46.210 --> 00:34:50.759
I really need a beer.

00:34:50.759 --> 00:34:56.280
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Patrick Mork: Water just doesn't do it.

00:34:56.280 --> 00:34:57.280
Anyway.

00:34:57.280 --> 00:34:59.309
We put together this promotion called 10-10-10.

00:34:59.309 --> 00:35:05.239
That was to celebrate 10 billion downloads
and that now seems like a long time ago, right?

00:35:05.239 --> 00:35:07.160
20 billion now, great stuff.

00:35:07.160 --> 00:35:09.520
We put together this promotion called 10-10-10.

00:35:09.520 --> 00:35:13.989
We had three key things we want today communicate
to consumers.

00:35:13.989 --> 00:35:22.420
10 days, 10-cent apps, 10 apps a day.

00:35:22.420 --> 00:35:23.420
Really simple.

00:35:23.420 --> 00:35:28.660
Yet, even though it was so simple, as you
can see going from top to bottom, we went

00:35:28.660 --> 00:35:32.450
through several different versions of creative
material to get to the right creative.

00:35:32.450 --> 00:35:36.210
You are not even seeing all of it because
it wouldn't fit on the slide.

00:35:36.210 --> 00:35:39.460
We went through version after version after
version after version after version of getting

00:35:39.460 --> 00:35:40.910
the creative right.

00:35:40.910 --> 00:35:46.510
And the point here is whether it's your thumbnails
or your video or your text descriptions, you

00:35:46.510 --> 00:35:50.299
iterate, iterate, iterate, iterate until you
get it right.

00:35:50.299 --> 00:35:54.579
And you test and test and test and test until
you get it right.

00:35:54.579 --> 00:35:56.549
Just like you do with your product.

00:35:56.549 --> 00:36:02.940
Creative is an iterative process, but it can
be so effective if you do it right.

00:36:02.940 --> 00:36:04.739
That brings us to the marketing plan.

00:36:04.739 --> 00:36:06.619
How do we build a plan?

00:36:06.619 --> 00:36:09.460
The way we look the marketing plans is quite
simple.

00:36:09.460 --> 00:36:10.810
Awareness.

00:36:10.810 --> 00:36:12.160
Trial.

00:36:12.160 --> 00:36:13.510
Purchase.

00:36:13.510 --> 00:36:14.780
And repeat.

00:36:14.780 --> 00:36:19.440
It has to be generally in that order.

00:36:19.440 --> 00:36:20.540
Why?

00:36:20.540 --> 00:36:25.450
Because if I basically start jumping into
purchase, it's kind of like I met this pretty

00:36:25.450 --> 00:36:29.069
girl at the Paul Oakenfold party tonight and
I say tomorrow morning, let's get married.

00:36:29.069 --> 00:36:30.380
Uh, no, you're weird.

00:36:30.380 --> 00:36:33.950
I am not going to call you again.

00:36:33.950 --> 00:36:37.089
It's basically, you have to go through the
steps of the process so that you can convince

00:36:37.089 --> 00:36:40.849
the consumer to get to the point where they
are going to consider a purchase.

00:36:40.849 --> 00:36:41.849
You start with awareness.

00:36:41.849 --> 00:36:44.259
Talk to them about what your product does.

00:36:44.259 --> 00:36:45.259
Where they should get it.

00:36:45.259 --> 00:36:46.259
Why it's unique.

00:36:46.259 --> 00:36:47.259
How it's different.

00:36:47.259 --> 00:36:49.510
There's a couple tools you can do here.

00:36:49.510 --> 00:36:52.359
This is not exhaustive, of course.

00:36:52.359 --> 00:36:53.359
Good PR.

00:36:53.359 --> 00:36:56.539
One of the most underused things I see in
this industry.

00:36:56.539 --> 00:37:03.059
Talk to the press, become their friends, make
sure that you send them their APKs, get them

00:37:03.059 --> 00:37:05.420
to your studio to see what you are working
on.

00:37:05.420 --> 00:37:10.260
It can be one of the most effective marketing
tools you can do and one of the cheapest is

00:37:10.260 --> 00:37:12.499
to get these people to write about your apps.

00:37:12.499 --> 00:37:16.410
I'll give you another tip.

00:37:16.410 --> 00:37:23.180
Getting people to write about your apps has
a direct influence on your search rankings

00:37:23.180 --> 00:37:25.089
in the play store.

00:37:25.089 --> 00:37:27.589
It's called web anchoring.

00:37:27.589 --> 00:37:31.609
It means that the more people kind of like
click on a link externally outside the play

00:37:31.609 --> 00:37:36.569
store and come to your page, because they've
read about you, the better you will index

00:37:36.569 --> 00:37:39.559
in the search rankings.

00:37:39.559 --> 00:37:42.049
Social.

00:37:42.049 --> 00:37:43.190
We talked about virality.

00:37:43.190 --> 00:37:45.020
Have a blog.

00:37:45.020 --> 00:37:46.289
Invite people to comment on it.

00:37:46.289 --> 00:37:47.739
Post your APKs on it.

00:37:47.739 --> 00:37:48.739
Create discussion.

00:37:48.739 --> 00:37:49.880
Get people to talk about it.

00:37:49.880 --> 00:37:51.900
Of course, other basic tools.

00:37:51.900 --> 00:37:53.589
Search ads, mobile ads.

00:37:53.589 --> 00:37:57.710
If you get to the point where you have the
available cash, well, TV or above-the-line

00:37:57.710 --> 00:37:58.710
media.

00:37:58.710 --> 00:38:01.680
Then we talk about trial.

00:38:01.680 --> 00:38:03.089
What can we do for trial?

00:38:03.089 --> 00:38:05.599
We talked about some of the business models
earlier today.

00:38:05.599 --> 00:38:07.109
We can have a free trial version.

00:38:07.109 --> 00:38:10.119
A version where I can use the app for 30 days.

00:38:10.119 --> 00:38:12.400
And then it's great because I don't have to
pay pour it and I can really figure out if

00:38:12.400 --> 00:38:13.759
I like it.

00:38:13.759 --> 00:38:15.430
Why is trial so important?

00:38:15.430 --> 00:38:17.640
Very simple, guys.

00:38:17.640 --> 00:38:23.180
It's very important because essentially many
consumers out there have never experienced

00:38:23.180 --> 00:38:25.450
content before.

00:38:25.450 --> 00:38:29.190
Many consumers out there are getting a smartphone
for the first time and they will think this

00:38:29.190 --> 00:38:30.400
content stuff is marvelous.

00:38:30.400 --> 00:38:36.729
Are they going to shell four five bucks or
euros if they have never tried content before?

00:38:36.729 --> 00:38:38.369
Probably not in some cases.

00:38:38.369 --> 00:38:42.960
By providing a free version of your application,
you generate that comfort level.

00:38:42.960 --> 00:38:46.170
When I was in the soft drinks business -- I
worked at Pepsi for many years.

00:38:46.170 --> 00:38:50.029
When we would launch a new drink in the market,
we would go out and give hundreds of thousands

00:38:50.029 --> 00:38:51.210
of cans to people.

00:38:51.210 --> 00:38:55.440
We'd have these pretty girls in mini skirts
and walking down in the middle of traffic

00:38:55.440 --> 00:38:59.190
and they would knock on your door, how about
a can of Pepsi max?

00:38:59.190 --> 00:39:00.609
Why did we do that?

00:39:00.609 --> 00:39:01.609
Trial.

00:39:01.609 --> 00:39:03.839
We want to make sure that the consumers love
the product.

00:39:03.839 --> 00:39:05.119
Hopefully they like the girls, too.

00:39:05.119 --> 00:39:06.829
But they love the product.

00:39:06.829 --> 00:39:09.259
So that when they go to the supermarket, they
have had it, tried it.

00:39:09.259 --> 00:39:10.729
Yeah, yeah, this is pretty good stuff.

00:39:10.729 --> 00:39:12.859
I think I'll buy a six-pack.

00:39:12.859 --> 00:39:15.799
Same thing goes for apps and games.

00:39:15.799 --> 00:39:17.210
We move on to purchase.

00:39:17.210 --> 00:39:19.759
Purchase, of course, there are other things
we can do.

00:39:19.759 --> 00:39:23.359
We can do direct response campaigns where
we are pushing people to download the app.

00:39:23.359 --> 00:39:24.359
They have heard about it.

00:39:24.359 --> 00:39:26.069
They have read about it on Tech Crunch.

00:39:26.069 --> 00:39:27.890
They have read the blogs.

00:39:27.890 --> 00:39:29.299
Talked to their friends about it.

00:39:29.299 --> 00:39:30.609
We can do notifications.

00:39:30.609 --> 00:39:34.739
We are saying, hey, guess what, you have now
been playing my game for 30 days, it's time

00:39:34.739 --> 00:39:35.739
to pay up.

00:39:35.739 --> 00:39:37.329
They may or may not do that.

00:39:37.329 --> 00:39:40.150
But, of course, at least they have had the
opportunity to try it because you have gone

00:39:40.150 --> 00:39:42.270
through step two.

00:39:42.270 --> 00:39:45.420
Lastly, repeat.

00:39:45.420 --> 00:39:47.829
Third rule of marketing.

00:39:47.829 --> 00:39:53.720
Always easier to get money from an existing
consumer than a new consumer.

00:39:53.720 --> 00:39:55.920
Makes sense but a lot of people don't follow
that rule?

00:39:55.920 --> 00:39:57.440
How do we keep the consumer interested.

00:39:57.440 --> 00:39:59.569
We heard about it in monetization panel.

00:39:59.569 --> 00:40:00.569
Right?

00:40:00.569 --> 00:40:02.200
You give them more don't.

00:40:02.200 --> 00:40:03.890
You upgrade your app frequently.

00:40:03.890 --> 00:40:05.799
You introduce new features.

00:40:05.799 --> 00:40:08.640
You give them new reasons to pay for this
stuff.

00:40:08.640 --> 00:40:10.420
You provide updates.

00:40:10.420 --> 00:40:14.019
You have CRM campaigns because you've actually
been talking to your consumers for the past

00:40:14.019 --> 00:40:19.989
three years and you have an email database
of 150,000 loyal fans who have downloaded

00:40:19.989 --> 00:40:21.289
your app.

00:40:21.289 --> 00:40:24.640
That's all about repeat.

00:40:24.640 --> 00:40:30.740
But we do have a pretty good idea already
of what kind of stuff works.

00:40:30.740 --> 00:40:34.729
So when I was talking about research earlier
in the session, we did this over the last

00:40:34.729 --> 00:40:36.019
couple of weeks.

00:40:36.019 --> 00:40:42.380
We put out a couple of questions on google.com/insights,
paid about a thousand bucks, whatever, basically

00:40:42.380 --> 00:40:46.569
asked people, what influences your decision
to install an app?

00:40:46.569 --> 00:40:48.789
U.S. only consumers, granted.

00:40:48.789 --> 00:40:53.039
We got about 1500 responses which is statistically
significant.

00:40:53.039 --> 00:40:55.359
And here's what they told us.

00:40:55.359 --> 00:40:58.479
I'm influenced by user reviews.

00:40:58.479 --> 00:41:00.440
Top apps lists.

00:41:00.440 --> 00:41:02.020
User ratings.

00:41:02.020 --> 00:41:03.020
And screen shots.

00:41:03.020 --> 00:41:04.020
Those are the top four.

00:41:04.020 --> 00:41:06.749
Now, obviously, it doesn't mean that they
are not influenced by the rest.

00:41:06.749 --> 00:41:10.769
But they are influenced by a lot of stuff
that you guys control.

00:41:10.769 --> 00:41:15.269
You control the user ratings because you can
control how good your product is and how frequently

00:41:15.269 --> 00:41:16.339
you update it.

00:41:16.339 --> 00:41:20.579
And how many cool features you build in and
how many crap features you take out.

00:41:20.579 --> 00:41:23.319
You control the text description.

00:41:23.319 --> 00:41:26.269
Because you read the great marketing slides
that talk about how important creative is

00:41:26.269 --> 00:41:30.880
and you built killer text, great assets and
super powerful video that have gone totally

00:41:30.880 --> 00:41:33.619
viral on YouTube.

00:41:33.619 --> 00:41:36.209
So you control a lot of that stuff.

00:41:36.209 --> 00:41:42.160
And search, you don't control that directly
but you do control it indirectly.

00:41:42.160 --> 00:41:44.599
Why?

00:41:44.599 --> 00:41:50.549
Tip number two: The other thing that affects
your search rankings in the Google Play store,

00:41:50.549 --> 00:41:53.119
is the number of installs.

00:41:53.119 --> 00:41:57.200
The more installs you have, the higher you
are on the search rankings.

00:41:57.200 --> 00:42:05.579
However, caveat, the more uninstalls you have,
the lower your search rankings, which is why

00:42:05.579 --> 00:42:07.750
you have to be careful when you use marketing.

00:42:07.750 --> 00:42:12.170
Because if your product is not good enough
and you get a lot of installs and then more

00:42:12.170 --> 00:42:17.260
uninstalls than installs because people figure
out your app was not good, it is going to

00:42:17.260 --> 00:42:20.239
penalize your search rankings.

